title	description	dataset_identifier	disease	authors	created	modified	accessed	landing_page	access_page	format	conforms_to	license	geography	apollo_location_code	iso_3166	iso_3166_1	iso_3166_1_alpha_3	apollo_enabled	on_olympus	population_required	iri
Counts of Acquired immune deficiency syndrome reported in UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: 1984-2005	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.62479008	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.62479008/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.62479008	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; HIV-1 in the United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021;http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000230

Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.301770000	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.301770000/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.301770000	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021
Counts of Babesiosis reported in UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: 2013-2016	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.35742006	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.35742006/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.35742006	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; Treponema pallidum subsp. pallidum in the United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021
Counts of Cryptosporidiosis reported in UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: 1999-2016	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"". In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/BD.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/BD.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/BD.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	BANGLADESH	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:BD	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of BANGLADESH; Aedes aegypti in region of BANGLADESH; Aedes albopictus in region of BANGLADESH; Dengue virus in region of BANGLADESH	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000894; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001403; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001404; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001669
Counts of Dengue hemorrhagic fever reported in BARBADOS: 1995-2012	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. Counts of Dengue hemorrhagic fever reported in CAYMAN ISLANDS: 1999-2012	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/KY.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/KY.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/KY.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	CAYMAN ISLANDS	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:KY	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of CAYMAN ISLANDS; Aedes aegypti in region of CAYMAN ISLANDS; Aedes albopictus in region of CAYMAN ISLANDS; Dengue virus in region of CAYMAN ISLANDS	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001449; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001271; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001272; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001638

Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/DM.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/DM.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/DM.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	DOMINICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:DM	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of DOMINICA; Aedes aegypti in region of DOMINICA; Aedes albopictus in region of DOMINICA; Dengue virus in region of DOMINICA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000885; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001237; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001238; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001688
Counts of Dengue hemorrhagic fever reported in DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: 1988-2012	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. Counts of Dengue hemorrhagic fever reported in GUAM: 2005-2005	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/GU.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/GU.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/GU.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	GUAM	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:GU	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of GUAM; Aedes aegypti in region of GUAM; Aedes albopictus in region of GUAM; Dengue virus in region of GUAM	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001554; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001622; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001623; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001553

Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Counts of Dengue hemorrhagic fever reported in KOREA (REPUBLIC OF): 2004-2004	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/KR.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/KR.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/KR.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	KOREA (REPUBLIC OF)	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:KR	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of KOREA (REPUBLIC OF); Aedes aegypti in region of KOREA (REPUBLIC OF); Aedes albopictus in region of KOREA (REPUBLIC OF); Dengue virus in region of KOREA (REPUBLIC OF)	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000977; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001241; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001242; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001679

Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/FM.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/FM.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/FM.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	MICRONESIA (FEDERATED STATES OF)	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:FM	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of MICRONESIA (FEDERATED STATES OF); Aedes aegypti in region of MICRONESIA (FEDERATED STATES OF); Aedes albopictus in region of MICRONESIA (FEDERATED STATES OF); Dengue virus in region of MICRONESIA (FEDERATED STATES OF)	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000871; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001315; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001316; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001836
Counts of Dengue hemorrhagic fever reported in MONGOLIA: 2004-2009	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Counts of Dengue hemorrhagic fever reported in PAPUA NEW GUINEA: 2009-2009	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/PG.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/PG.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/PG.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	PAPUA NEW GUINEA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:PG	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of PAPUA NEW GUINEA; Aedes aegypti in region of PAPUA NEW GUINEA; Aedes albopictus in region of PAPUA NEW GUINEA; Dengue virus in region of PAPUA NEW GUINEA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000971; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001263; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001264; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001649

Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/MF.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/MF.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/MF.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	SAINT MARTIN (FRENCH PART)	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:MF	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of SAINT MARTIN (FRENCH PART); Aedes aegypti in region of SAINT MARTIN (FRENCH PART); Aedes albopictus in region of SAINT MARTIN (FRENCH PART); Dengue virus in region of SAINT MARTIN (FRENCH PART)	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001504; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001375; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001376; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001645
Counts of Dengue hemorrhagic fever reported in SAINT VINCENT AND THE GRENADINES: 1999-2012	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/TC.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/TC.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/TC.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	TURKS AND CAICOS ISLANDS	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:TC	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of TURKS AND CAICOS ISLANDS; Aedes aegypti in region of TURKS AND CAICOS ISLANDS; Aedes albopictus in region of TURKS AND CAICOS ISLANDS; Dengue virus in region of TURKS AND CAICOS ISLANDS	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001446; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001327; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001328; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001693
Counts of Dengue hemorrhagic fever reported in TUVALU: 2004-2009	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/TV.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/TV.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/TV.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	TUVALU	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:TV	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of TUVALU; Aedes aegypti in region of TUVALU; Aedes albopictus in region of TUVALU; Dengue virus in region of TUVALU	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000928; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001267; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001268; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001704

Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/WF.20927009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/WF.20927009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/WF.20927009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	WALLIS AND FUTUNA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:WF	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of WALLIS AND FUTUNA; Aedes aegypti in Wallis and Futuna Islands; Aedes albopictus in Wallis and Futuna Islands; Dengue virus in Wallis and Futuna Islands	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001492; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001901; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001902; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001903
Counts of Dengue reported in AMERICAN SAMOA: 1955-2010	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Counts of Dengue reported in BARBADOS: 1977-2012	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/BB.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/BB.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/BB.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	BARBADOS	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:BB	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of BARBADOS; Aedes aegypti in region of BARBADOS; Aedes albopictus in region of BARBADOS; Dengue virus in region of BARBADOS	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000952; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001303; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001304; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001683

In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/CA.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/CA.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/CA.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	CANADA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:CA	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of CANADA; Aedes aegypti in region of CANADA; Aedes albopictus in region of CANADA; Dengue virus in region of CANADA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000356; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001377; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001378; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001659
Counts of Dengue reported in CAYMAN ISLANDS: 1995-2012	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"". "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/GP.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/GP.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/GP.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	GUADELOUPE	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:GP	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of GUADELOUPE; Aedes aegypti in region of GUADELOUPE; Aedes albopictus in region of GUADELOUPE; Dengue virus in region of GUADELOUPE	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001444; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001363; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001364; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001724
Counts of Dengue reported in GUAM: 1983-2010	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/GU.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/GU.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/GU.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	GUAM	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:GU	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of GUAM; Aedes aegypti in region of GUAM; Aedes albopictus in region of GUAM; Dengue virus in region of GUAM	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001554; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001622; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001623; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001553

In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/JM.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/JM.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/JM.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	JAMAICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:JM	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of JAMAICA; Aedes aegypti in region of JAMAICA; Aedes albopictus in region of JAMAICA; Dengue virus in region of JAMAICA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000951; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001269; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001270; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001723
Counts of Dengue reported in JAPAN: 1999-2010	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Counts of Dengue reported in MARTINIQUE: 1975-2012	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/MQ.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/MQ.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/MQ.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	MARTINIQUE	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:MQ	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of MARTINIQUE; Aedes aegypti in region of MARTINIQUE; Aedes albopictus in region of MARTINIQUE; Dengue virus in region of MARTINIQUE	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001440; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001247; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001248; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001674

Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/NC.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/NC.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/NC.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	NEW CALEDONIA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:NC	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of NEW CALEDONIA; Aedes aegypti in region of NEW CALEDONIA; Aedes albopictus in region of NEW CALEDONIA; Dengue virus in region of NEW CALEDONIA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001543; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001814; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001822; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001711
Counts of Dengue reported in NEW ZEALAND: 1979-2010	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. Counts of Dengue reported in PERU: 1988-2012	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/PE.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/PE.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/PE.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	PERU	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:PE	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of PERU; Aedes aegypti in region of PERU; Aedes albopictus in region of PERU; Dengue virus in region of PERU	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000854; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001409; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001410; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001720
