Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/VC.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/VC.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/VC.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	SAINT VINCENT AND THE GRENADINES	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:VC	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of SAINT VINCENT AND THE GRENADINES; Aedes aegypti in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines; Aedes albopictus in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines; Dengue virus in Saint Vincent and the Grenadines	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000800; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001365; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001366; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001691
Counts of Dengue reported in SAMOA: 1979-2008	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Counts of Dengue reported in TIMOR-LESTE: 1985-2006	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/TL.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/TL.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/TL.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	TIMOR-LESTE	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:TL	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of TIMOR-LESTE; Aedes aegypti in region of TIMOR-LESTE; Aedes albopictus in region of TIMOR-LESTE; Dengue virus in region of TIMOR-LESTE	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000920; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001359; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001360; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001665

Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/VU.38362002	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/VU.38362002/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/VU.38362002	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	VANUATU	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:VU	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of VANUATU; Aedes aegypti in Vanuatu; Aedes albopictus in Vanuatu; Dengue virus in Vanuatu	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000869; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001261; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001262; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001905
Counts of Dengue reported in VENEZUELA (BOLIVARIAN REPUBLIC OF): 1960-2012	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in ARGENTINA: 1998-2005	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/AR.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/AR.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/AR.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	ARGENTINA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:AR	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of ARGENTINA; Aedes aegypti in region of ARGENTINA; Aedes albopictus in region of ARGENTINA; Dengue virus in region of ARGENTINA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000802; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001349; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001350; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001672

Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/BO.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/BO.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/BO.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	BOLIVIA (PLURINATIONAL STATE OF)	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:BO	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of BOLIVIA (PLURINATIONAL STATE OF); Aedes aegypti in region of BOLIVIA (PLURINATIONAL STATE OF); Aedes albopictus in region of BOLIVIA (PLURINATIONAL STATE OF); Dengue virus in region of BOLIVIA (PLURINATIONAL STATE OF)	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000807; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001387; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001388; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001727
Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in BRAZIL: 1980-2005	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in COSTA RICA: 1988-2005	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/CR.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/CR.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/CR.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	COSTA RICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:CR	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of COSTA RICA; Aedes aegypti in region of COSTA RICA; Aedes albopictus in region of COSTA RICA; Dengue virus in region of COSTA RICA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000959; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001319; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001320; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001640

Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/PF.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/PF.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/PF.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	FRENCH POLYNESIA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:PF	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of FRENCH POLYNESIA; Aedes aegypti in region of FRENCH POLYNESIA; Aedes albopictus in region of FRENCH POLYNESIA; Dengue virus in region of FRENCH POLYNESIA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001552; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001816; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001824; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001834
Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in GRENADA: 1969-2005	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"". Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in INDONESIA: 1968-1996	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/ID.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/ID.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/ID.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	INDONESIA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:ID	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of INDONESIA; Aedes aegypti in region of INDONESIA; Aedes albopictus in region of INDONESIA; Dengue virus in region of INDONESIA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000937; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001347; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001348; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001643

"	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/MQ.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/MQ.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/MQ.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	MARTINIQUE	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:MQ	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of MARTINIQUE; Aedes aegypti in region of MARTINIQUE; Aedes albopictus in region of MARTINIQUE; Dengue virus in region of MARTINIQUE	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001440; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001247; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001248; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001674
Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in MEXICO: 1971-2005	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/MX.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/MX.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/MX.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	MEXICO	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:MX	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of MEXICO; Aedes aegypti in region of MEXICO; Aedes albopictus in region of MEXICO; Dengue virus in region of MEXICO	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000944; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001321; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001322; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001692

Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/NU.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/NU.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/NU.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	NIUE	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:NU	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of NIUE; Aedes aegypti in region of NIUE; Aedes albopictus in region of NIUE; Dengue virus in region of NIUE	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001486; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001815; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001823; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001700
Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in NORTHERN MARIANA ISLANDS: 2001-2001	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in SAINT KITTS AND NEVIS: 1960-2005	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/KN.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/KN.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/KN.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	SAINT KITTS AND NEVIS	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:KN	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of SAINT KITTS AND NEVIS; Aedes aegypti in region of SAINT KITTS AND NEVIS; Aedes albopictus in region of SAINT KITTS AND NEVIS; Dengue virus in region of SAINT KITTS AND NEVIS	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000830; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001289; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001290; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001706

Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/SR.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/SR.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/SR.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	SURINAME	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:SR	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of SURINAME; Aedes aegypti in region of SURINAME; Aedes albopictus in region of SURINAME; Dengue virus in region of SURINAME	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000892; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001389; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001390; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001697
Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in THAILAND: 1958-1996	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Counts of Dengue without warning signs reported in URUGUAY: 2003-2005	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/UY.722862003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/UY.722862003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/UY.722862003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	URUGUAY	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:UY	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of URUGUAY; Aedes aegypti in Uruguay; Aedes albopictus in Uruguay; Dengue virus in Uruguay	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000963; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001369; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001370; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001728

In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.417093003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.417093003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.417093003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; Aedes aegypti in the United States; Aedes albopictus in the United States; West Nile virus in the United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001177; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001415; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001421
Counts of Disorder of nervous system caused by West Nile virus reported in UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: 2002-2016	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.186634008	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.186634008/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.186634008	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; Hepatitis C virus in United States; Hepatitis E virus in United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000005354; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000005356
Counts of Human anaplasmosis caused by Anaplasma phagocytophilum reported in UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: 2010-2016	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"". "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.128241005	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.128241005/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.128241005	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021
Counts of Influenza reported in UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: 1919-1951	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.6142004	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.6142004/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.6142004	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; Influenza virus in the United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000420

Counts of Lobar pneumonia reported in UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: 1919-1919	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.278516003	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.278516003/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.278516003	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; Streptococcus pneumoniae in the United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001425

Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.75116005	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.75116005/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.75116005	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; Chlamydia psittaci in the United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001856
Counts of Pellagra reported in UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: 1923-1932	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.30242009	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.30242009/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.30242009	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; Streptococcus sp. 'group A' in the United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001872
Counts of Shigellosis reported in UNITED STATES OF AMERICA: 1999-2016	"Project Tycho datasets contain case counts for reported disease conditions for countries around the world. The Project Tycho data curation team extracts these case counts from various reputable sources, typically from national or international health authorities, such as the US Centers for Disease Control or the World Health Organization. These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.36188001	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.36188001/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.36188001	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; Shigella in the United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001840

These original data sources include both open- and restricted-access sources. For restricted-access sources, the Project Tycho team has obtained permission for redistribution from data contributors. All datasets contain case count data that are identical to counts published in the original source and no counts have been modified in any way by the Project Tycho team. The Project Tycho team has pre-processed datasets by adding new variables, such as standard disease and location identifiers, that improve data interpretability. We also formatted the data into a standard data format.  Each Project Tycho dataset contains case counts for a specific condition (e.g. measles) and for a specific country (e.g. The United States). Case counts are reported per time interval. In addition to case counts, datasets include information about these counts (attributes), such as the location, age group, subpopulation, diagnostic certainty, place of acquisition, and the source from which we extracted case counts. One dataset can include many series of case count time intervals, such as ""US measles cases as reported by CDC"", or ""US measles cases reported by WHO"", or ""US measles cases that originated abroad"", etc.   Depending on the intended use of a dataset, we recommend a few data processing steps before analysis: - Analyze missing data: Project Tycho datasets do not include time intervals for which no case count was reported (for many datasets, time series of case counts are incomplete, due to incompleteness of source documents) and users will need to add time intervals for which no count value is available. Project Tycho datasets do include time intervals for which a case count value of zero was reported. - Separate cumulative from non-cumulative time interval series. Case count time series in Project Tycho datasets can be ""cumulative"" or ""fixed-intervals"". Cumulative case count time series consist of overlapping case count intervals starting on the same date, but ending on different dates. For example, each interval in a cumulative count time series can start on January 1st, but end on January 7th, 14th, 21st, etc. It is common practice among public health agencies to report cases for cumulative time intervals. Case count series with fixed time intervals consist of mutually exclusive time intervals that all start and end on different dates and all have identical length (day, week, month, year). Given the different nature of these two types of case count data, we indicated this with an attribute for each count value, named ""PartOfCumulativeCountSeries"".  "	10.25337/T7/ptycho.v2.0/US.186090001	null	Willem Van Panhuis; Anne Cross; Donald Burke	2018-01-30	null	null	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/US.186090001/	http://www.tycho.pitt.edu/tycho/dataset/download/US.186090001	CSV	Project Tycho Data Standard; bsg-s000718	Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International	UNITED STATES OF AMERICA	https://www.iso.org/obp/ui/#iso:code:3166:US	null	null	null	FALSE	FALSE	humans in region of UNITED STATES OF AMERICA; Salmonella typhi in the United States; Salmonella paratyphi A in the United States	http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000000021; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000001437; http://www.pitt.edu/obc/IDE_0000005550
